definition.value: A terpenoid trilactone found in extracts of Ginkgo biloba.

5,6,7,8-Tetrahydroquinoline in whith the hydrogens at position 6 are substituted by a 3-azabutyl group and a 3,4-dimethoxyphenyl group. (S configuration). It is found in the herb kanna (Sceletium tortuosum).
A member of the class of chalcones that is trans-chalcone hydroxylated at C-2', -4 and -4'.
A member of the class of naphthopyrans that is 4,10-dihydro-3H-naphtho[2,3-c]pyran-3-yl]acetic acid bearing additional methyl, hydroxy and oxo substituents at positions 1, 9 and 10 respectively.
A methoxybenzene carrying methoxy groups at positions 1, 3 and 5. It has been found to be a biomarker of flavonoid consumption in humans.
The anhydrous form of the monohydrochloride salt of ciprofloxacin.
Isoquinoline in which the hydrogens at positions 6 and 8 are substituted by hydroxy groups, and those at positions 1 and 3 are substituted by methyl groups.
A member of the class of phenols that is phenol substituted by a 1-hydroxyethyl group at position 4.
An anthracycline antibiotic that is 13-deoxycarminomycin substituted at position 10 by a carboxy group.

A cytotoxic anthracycline antibiotic that is produced by Streptomyces peucetius var. carminatus (a biochemical mutant of Streptomyces peucetius var. caesius), and is active against P-388 murine leukemia.

An aminoglycoside antibiotic that is (1S,3S)-3-ethyl-3,5,12-trihydroxy-10-methoxy-6,11-dioxo-1,2,3,4,6,11-hexahydrotetracene having a 3-amino-2,3,6-trideoxy-alpha-L-lyxo-hexopyranosyl residue attached at position 1 via a glycosidic linkage.
A anthracycline antibiotic that is a cardiotoxic metabolite of carminomycin obtained by formal reduction of the carbonyl group.

An aminoglycoside antibiotic that is (1S,3S)-3,5,12-trihydroxy-3-(1-hydroxyethyl)-10-methoxy-6,11-dioxo-1,2,3,4,6,11-hexahydrotetracene having a 3-amino-2,3,6-trideoxy-alpha-L-lyxo-hexopyranosyl residue attached at position 1 via a glycosidic linkage.
A methoxyisoflavone in which the methoxy group is located at position 4' together with three additional hydroxy substituents at positions 2' 5 and 7.
A berberine alkaloid that is  berbine substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 2, 3, 9 and 10.
An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is hexanedioic acid containing a double bond between positions 2 and 3, an oxo group at position 4, and two chlorine atoms (at positions 2 and 5).
